Podetia bright yellowish green, cupless or with perforated and deformed cups, UV- or UV+ white (squamatic acid). Stalk with many longitudinal splits. Primary squamules rather large, 2-4(-8) mm long, 2.5-4(-6) mm wide
Podetia goblet-shaped, ending with a broad, regular or marginally proliferating cup
Podetia bacilliform or branched, without cups or with small, irregular cups
Thallus yellowish green, KC+ yellow, with usnic acid. Apothecia and pycnidia yellowish to pale brown
Thallus without a yellowish hue, KC- (usnic acid absent) or KC+ reddish. Apothecia and pycnidia dark brown
Podetia without a verruculose cortex. With homosekikaic and sekikaic acids
Podetia with a verruculose cortex, without homosekikaic and sekikaic acids (difficult group, TLC needed)
Acetone extract of thallus KC-, with grayanic acid
Acetone extract of thallus KC+ red, with merochlorophaeic acid
Thallus yellowish green, KC+ yellow, with usnic acid
Thallus green, greenish grey to brown, without a yellowish hue, KC-, without usnic acid
Podetia up to 5(-8) cm tall, yellowish green in upper part, often bluish at base. Usually on moist acid soil
Podetia rarely over 2 cm tall, clearly yellowish, not bluish at the base. Usually on wood
Podetia with wide, irregular, distinctly perforated funnels with often toothed, inrolled margins
Podetia bacilliform or with small, non-perforated cups
Podetia and basal squamules esorediate (but often coarsely verruculose-microsquamulose), with perlatolic acid
Podetia and often also basal squamules sorediate, without perlatolic acid
Primary squamules persistent, well-developed, 2-4 mm long, forming small mats, often with bright red spots. With barbatic acid
Primary squamules small, sparse or evanescent, without bright red spots. Without barbatic acid
Podetia brownish green to dirty brown, with homosekikaic acid
Podetia pale grey-green, sometimes partly browned at base, with squamatic acid
Podetia shrubby, densely branched, forming tufts
Podetia not shrubby, simple or sparingly branched in upper part
Thallus yellowish green, KC+ yellow, with usnic acid
Thallus greenish grey to brown, KC-, without usnic acid
Podetia erect, with a well-visible main axis, usually much branched at apex, the tips very thin, forked, subulate, often bearing scattered cups
Podetia without a well-visible main axis, the tips thick, acute and almost spiny, always without cups
Podetia matt, not darkened at tips, with a thin cortex, the tips producing abundant bluish crystals in the herbarium
Podetia slightly glossy, darkened at tips, with a thick cortex, the tips not producing bluish crystals in the herbarium
Branching mainly polytomous, with widely open axils. Inner surface of podetia not powdery. Medulla usually UV-
keyData.leadSpecies: Cladonia uncialis (L.) F.H. Wigg. subsp. uncialis

keyData.leadText: Branching mainly dichotomous, with many closed axils (c. 60%). Inner surface of podetia finely powdery.  Medulla usually UV+ white (squamatic acid)
keyData.leadSpecies: Cladonia uncialis (L.) F.H. Wigg. subsp. biuncialis (Hoffm.) M. Choisy

keyData.leadText: Thallus K+ yellow, with atranorin
Thallus K- or K+ brownish, without atranorin

Branching dense and strongly divergent, often forming compact tufts. Algal layer markedly discontinuous, the algae forming dispersed, raised, green areoles separated by conspicuous white lines. With rangiformic acid. Lichen of dry, sunny sites

Branching weakly dense and divergent, usually not giving rise to compact tufts. Algal layer continuous or forming a mosaic intersected by thin white lines, or dispersed in scattered (not raised) clusters. Without rangiformic acid. Lichen of mesic sites
Podetia dark to pale brown, glossy, the base strongly melanotic
Podetia greenish grey to brown, opaque, the base not melanotic
Podetia with open axillary or terminal funnels which proliferate from margins, thus terminating in a cup-like perforation with spinulose margins. With squamatic acid (UV+ white)
Podetia usually with pointed ends, the axils closed or only tips longitudinally open in fertile specimens. Without squamatic acid (UV-)
Apothecia and pycnidial slime scarlet red. Necrotic bases of podetia often turning orange
Apothecia and pycnidial slime brown. Necrotic bases of podetia grey, brown or black
Podetia almost fully corticate, grey-green, KC-, without usnic acid, always cupless
Podetia often with schizidia or microsquamules, yellowish green, KC+ yellow, with usnic acid, often with cups
Podetia densely macrosquamulose throughout. Cups usually absent
Podetia not densely macrosquamulose (sometimes microsquamulose in lower part). Cups always present
Podetia mostly covered with microsquamules. Cups rather narrow
Podetia with a smooth, areolate to granular cortex. Cups wide

Podetia dark yellowish green, with blackened parts especially at base and along the margins of cups, P+ yellow, UV+ white (thamnolic acid) or K-, P- (squamatic acid), without crystals on the surface of dead thalli

Podetia dark yellowish green, with blackened parts especially at base and along the margins of cups, P+ yellow, UV+ white (thamnolic acid) or K-, P- (squamatic acid), without crystals on the surface of dead thalli
Podetia pale greenish yellow, without blackened parts, always K-, P- (without thamnolic or squamatic acids), with needle-like crystals (zeorin) on the surface of dead thalli
Podetia (especially in the upper part) with cortex disintegrating into convex, irregular warts or granules. Dead thalli with crystal needles (zeorin)
Podetia with a continuous cortex or cortex disintegrating into flat, plate-like areoles. Dead thalli without crystal needles (barbatic acid)
Thallus K+ yellow or K+ yellow turning red
Thallus K-
Thallus K+ yellow turning red
Thallus K+ yellow
Thallus K+ yellow rapidly turning red. Squamules often bluish, brownish or yellowish beneath. Podetia cupless, club-shaped. Mostly on subacid, sandy soils
Thallus K+ yellow slowly turning red. Squamules pure white beneath. Podetia not club-shaped, branched or sometimes with cups. Mostly on calcareous soils
Primary thallus crustose, of persistent granules
Primary thallus distinctly squamulose
Primary squamules very fragile, (6-)12-25 mm long
Primary squamules not fragile, <10 mm long
Primary squamules large (3-6 x 2-4 mm). On dry calcareous soil
Primary squamules smaller. On acid substrata
Podetia longitudinally cracked, esorediate, without squamules, the tips bearing apothecia
Podetia not cracked, microsquamulose or with small corticate granules
Basal squamules large, not coralloid-branched. Podetia > 2 cm tall, densely microsquamulose
Basal squamules small, crowded, coralloid-branched. Podetia <2 cm tall, thin, often covered with corticate granules
Thallus P+ yellow or yellow-orange
Thallus P-
Primary squamules C+ bright emerald green
Primary squamules C-

Primary squamules 4-8 mm long, 1-2 mm wide, brownish green above, yellowish white beneath. Podetia with cups (usually proliferating from the center), strongly melanotic at base. Species found below the subalpine belt

Primary squamules 3-6(-10) mm long, 3-6(-8) mm wide, glaucescent to rarely olive-green and often verruculose or checkered above, white beneath. Podetia without cups, not melanotic at base. Species found in the subalpine and alpine belts
Podetia goblet-shaped, ending with a broad, regular cup (difficult group, TLC needed)
Podetia bacilliform or branched, without cups or with small, irregular cups
Acetone extract of thallus KC-, with grayanic acid
Acetone extract of thallus KC+ yellow or KC+ red, with sekikaic or merochlorophaeic acid, without grayanic acid
Podetia C+ yellow, UV– or UV+ white, with sekikaic and homosekikaic acids
Podetia C+ weakly red, UV+ bluish white. With merochlorophaeic acid
Podetia yellowish green, KC+ yellow, with usnic acid. Apothecia  (almost always present) yellowish to very pale brown
Podetia not yellowish green, KC-, without usnic acid. Apothecia absent or dark brown
Podetia usually simple and bacilliform, (if sparingly branched with closed axils), mostly without cups
Podetia branched and without cups, or with open axils giving rise to perforate, cup-like funnels
Podetia densely squamulose, with narrow, irregular cups
Podetia not densely squamulose, with or without cups
Podetia dark to pale brown, glossy, the base strongly melanotic
Podetia greenish grey to brown, opaque, the base not melanotic
Thallus of cylindrical white pseudopodetia densely covered in corticate to leprose granules (phyllocladia)
Thallus without phyllocladia
Phyllocladia greenish, leprose
Phyllocladia whitish, corticate
Thallus (especially phyllocladia) P+ orange-red, with stictic acid (reaction often slow!)
Thallus P- or P+ yellow, without stictic acid
Pseudopodetia distinctly tomentose in lower part. On soil
Pseudopodetia not distinctly tomentose. On rock
Phyllocladia not peltate, cylindrical, branched, becoming coralloid
Phyllocladia at first verrucose, the largest ones usually peltate, flattened or concave, at least some of them with a darker central part and paler margins
Pseudopodetia with a felt-like surface, esorediate. Phyllocladia usually not confluent
Pseudopodetia with a glabrous surface, often sorediate. Phyllocladia partly confluent, forming plate-like squamules
keyData.leadSpecies: Stereocaulon vesuvianum var. nodulosum (Wallr.) I.M. Lamb

keyData.leadText: Thallus sorediate
Thallus without soredia
Primary thallus persistent, of basal phyllocladia and cephalodia forming a compact mat
Primary thallus ephemeral, usually totally absent in mature specimens
Soredia gathered in well-delimited, capitate soralia.  Phyllocladia present, flattened-verruciform, but soon disappearing into farinose soredia
Soredia effuse, or in spathulate apical expansions of the branches. True phyllocladia absent
Phyllocladia squamulose, fan-shaped with a sorediate lower surface. Pseudopodetia to 0.5 cm tall, without terminal soralia
Phyllocladia wart-like or cylindrical, rarely branched, esorediate. Pseudopodetia 2–5 mm tall, with terminal, globose soralia
On rock
On soil, terricolous mosses and plant debris
Phyllocladia peltate, with a darker centre
Phyllocladia not peltate, without a darker centre
Phyllocladia squamulose, more or less deeply divided into cylindrical lobes. With lobaric acid
Phyllocladia granular-verruciform, small. Without lobaric acid
Primary thallus persistent, of basal phyllocladia and cephalodia forming a compact, soil-binding mat
Primary thallus ephemeral, usually totally absent in mature specimens
Cephalodia containing Nostoc, verruciform to globose, pale bluish grey to pinkish white, with a smooth surface
Cephalodia containing Stigonema, dark reddish brown to blackish brown, with a scabrid surface
Pseudopodetia with an ash-grey tomentum. Cephalodia usually well-visible, localized in the parts without phyllocladia
Pseudopodetia with a whitish to creamy pink tomentum. Cephalodia scarce, not well-visible, partly hidden in the tomentum (difficult group: observation of cephalodia needed for identification)

Cephalodia elongate-tubercular, violet brown. Phyllocladia usually not concealing the pseudopodetial branches. Pseudopodetia very brittle, often branched from near base, lacking a well-defined main stem

Cephalodia globose, pale brown or blue-green. Phyllocladia usually crowded and largely concealing pseudopodetial branches as viewed from above. Pseudopodetia not especially brittle, usually with a well-defined main stem
Cephalodia pale brown, sparsely tomentose, with Nostoc or Stigonema, Phyllocladia deeply crenate-squamulose to digitate-squamulose
Cephalodia blue-green, with Nostoc. Phyllocladia verrucose to thickly crenate-squamulose
Lichen with a primary, squamulose to crustose thallus, and erect fruticose podetia
Lichen without two types of thallus
Pseudopodetia farinose-sorediate throughout. Apothecia black
Pseudopodetia esorediate, with a smooth surface. Apothecia pink to brown
Apothecia dome-shaped since the beginning, pink, K-
Apothecia not dome-shaped, brown-red (or, if pink, then K+ orange then blood-red)
Thallus K+ yellow turning red, with norstictic acid as the main substance
Thallus K+ yellow, norstictic acid absent or in traces
Thallus with radiating marginal lobes. Stipe of the apothecia corticate in lower part
Thallus without marginal lobes. Stipe of the apothecia usually ecorticate
Apothecia brown. K- or K+ yellow
Apothecia pink to pale red-brown. K+ orange turning blood-red
Thallus grey, brown or black, without usnic acid
Thallus green to yellowish green when dry, with usnic acid
Thallus with Trentepohlia. Restricted to maritime habitats, mostly on rock
Thallus with chlorococcoid photobionts. Not restricted to maritime habitats
Medulla very thin, hardly visible. Thallus very brittle when dry, esorediate
Medulla thick, well-evident. Thallus not brittle, sorediate
Branches distinctly flattened
Branches terete
Cortex and subcortex C+ red. Medulla of the basal holdfast usually ochre-coloured
Cortex C-, subcortex C+ red. Medulla of the basal holdfast white
Lobes inflated, hollow inside, grey on upper surface, black on lower surface, with apical capitate soralia
Lichens with a different combination of characters
Thallus distinctly flattened and clearly dorsiventral
Thallus not dorsiventral
Thallus K+ yellow, with cylindrical to coralloid isidia
Thallus K-, without isidia or with granular isidia
Isidia mainly marginal. Thallus wrinkled, often white-maculate
keyData.leadSpecies: Platismatia glauca (L.) W.L. Culb. & C.F. Culb.

keyData.leadText: Isidia mainly laminal. Thallus not wrinkled and not maculate
Medulla C+ red
keyData.leadSpecies: Pseudevernia furfuracea var. ceratea (Ach.) D. Hawksw.

keyData.leadText: Medulla C-
Thallus with long marginal cilia
Thallus without marginal cilia (sometimes with marginal spinules)
Lobes narrow, 0.1-0.5(-0.8) mm wide. Apothecial margin usually spinulose
Lobes > 1 mm wide. Apothecial margin usually not spinulose
Thallus K+ yellow, pale grey on one surface, white on the other, with marginal soralia
Thallus with a different combination of characters
Thallus hairy. Apothecial disc orange, K+ red
Thallus not hairy. Apothecia not orange and K+ red
Thallus lobes 0.05-0.3 mm wide, ascending, forming up to 1 cm wide, very brittle tufts
Thallus lobes >0.5 mm wide, not forming brittle tufts
On bark. Lobes to 10 mm long. Apothecia frequent
On soil (very rarely on bark). Lobes >10 mm long. Apothecia rare
Medulla C+ and KC+ pink, with gyrophoric acid
Medulla C-, KC- or C+, KC+ yellow, without gyrophoric acid
Medulla P-. Surface ±smooth. Marginal pseudocyphellae in lines. Lobes less than 4 mm wide, strongly channelled and inrolled, and appearing tubular
Medulla P+ red. Surface ridged and pitted. Marginal pseudocyphellae ±absent (most pseudocyphellae laminal). Lobes more than 4 mm wide, more or less channelled but not appearing tubular
Thallus very soft, long-pendent in humid forests, pale grey to whitish grey, K+ bright yellow (atranorin),  with a cottony medulla, without vegetative diaspores and pseudocyphellae, mostly sterile
Species with a different combination of characters
Thallus thread-like
Thallus not thread-like
Thallus isidiate, with a more or less scrobiculate surface
Thallus not isidiate (sometimes with short lateral spinules), with a smooth surface
Thallus with distinct, white, raised pseudocyphellae. On soil in alpine situations
Thallus without pseudocyphellae or with inconspicuous, not raised pseudocyphellae. On bark or siliceous rocks, rarely on soil
Thallus densely and divergently branched, dark brown-black, never sorediate, forming a decumbent mat attached by hapters to the rock. Distance between branches max 3 mm
Thallus usually not so densely branched, grey to brown-black, sometimes with soralia, shrubby or pendulous, attached at one end, without hapters. Distance between branches usually >3 mm
Branches up to 0.5 mm thick, mainly regularly terete and smooth. Internodes 1-3 mm long
Branches 0.1-0.2 mm thick, terete but usually flattened at tips and with nodular swellings. Internodes up to 1 mm long
Thallus much longer than wide in outline, long-pendent or prostrate, the branches without lateral spinules
Thallus c. as long as wide in outline, shrubby, the branches often with lateral spinules
Soralia bright yellow, with vulpinic acid
Soralia absent, or whitish, without vulpinic acid
Thallus pale, whitish grey to pale brownish grey, K+ yellow, KC+ red, with barbatolic acid. Pseudocyphellae absent or poorly evident
Thallus usually dark, or, if pale and KC+ red, with distinct pseudocyphellae and without barbatolic acid
Thallus K+ yellow, KC+ red, with alectorialic and barbatolic acids
Thallus K-, KC-
Basal parts of thallus more or less concolorous with the apical parts
Basal parts of thallus much darker than the apical parts
Soralia white, with isidioid spinules, P+ red
Soralia greenish black, without isidioid spinules, P-
Soralia absent. Medulla P+ red (fumarprotocetraric acid)
Soralia present, with tuft of spinules. Medulla and soralia P-
keyData.leadSpecies: Bryoria smithii (Du Rietz) Brodo & D. Hawksw.

keyData.leadText: Thallus with isidia. Cortex K+ bright yellow, with atranorin
Thallus without isidia. Cortex without atranorin
Thallus black to brown-black, firmly attached to siliceous rocks near or above treeline
Thallus different, if dark-coloured not firmly attached to rocks near or above treeline
Thallus without pseudocyphellae
Thallus with pseudocyphellae
Thallus either tomentose, blastidiate and sterile or glabrous, not blastidiate and fertile, the ascospores 1(-2) septate and brown
Thallus never tomentose and blastidiate, the ascospores never septate
Thallus not coralloid, white-maculate, consisting of imbricate or dispersed squamules-branches interconnected by abundant rhizomorphs
keyData.leadSpecies: Circinaria crespiana (V.J. Rico) Sohrabi & V.J. Rico

keyData.leadText: Thallus coralloid, not white-maculate, without rhizomorphs
Branches distinctly flattened at base. Ascospores subglobose
Branches rounded at base. Ascospores ellipsoid
All branches with distinctly wider main stems. Medulla I+ violet-blue
Sterile branches all of equal width. Medulla I-
On bark
On soil
Thallus grey to glaucous green, not glossy
keyData.leadSpecies: Circinaria hispida (Mereschk.) A. Nordin, Savić & Tibell

keyData.leadText: Thallus brown to dark brown, more or less glossy
Medulla pale ochre-coloured (secalonic acid), C+ and KC+ yellow. Pseudocyphellae, punctiform, raised, often surrounded by black projections. Very rare species
keyData.leadSpecies: Cetraria obtusata (Schaer.) van den Boom & Sipman

keyData.leadText: Medulla white, C-, KC-. Pseudocyphellae not surrounded by black projections. Widespread and often common species
Branches c. 1 mm wide, terete or angular, with longitudinal furrows, forming irregular tufts. Pseudocyphellae abundant, distinct, deeply depressed. Medulla often hollow in basal parts
Branches c. 0.5 mm wide, terete, with a smooth surface, forming compact tufts. Pseudocyphellae scattered, poorly visible, flat to slightly depressed. Medulla solid in basal parts
Medulla forming a compact strand visible as a filament by stretching the thallus
Medulla not forming such a compact, thread-like strand
Thallus very long-pendent, 50-200(-300) cm long, almost unbranched, becoming ecorticate, with numerous perpendicular fibrils. Central axis very thick, (70-85% of total thickness), I+ blue
Thallus shorter, corticate, more or less richly branched. Central axis thinner (max. 65%), I-
Cortex with a red-orange pigment at least in basal parts of thallus (not to be confused with necrotic zones in specimens infected by fungi, or fallen to the ground)
Cortex without a red-orange pigment  (reddish pigments, if present, limited to the medulla)
Red pigment distributed as minute purple-red spots. Lateral branches often narrowed at attachment point. Cortex moderately thin (4-8%); medulla often yellow close to axis; central axis thin (19-37%)

Red pigment ± uniformly distributed (sometimes visible in basal parts only). Lateral branches not narrowed at attachment point. Cortex thick (9-13%); medulla white throughout; central axis thicker (40-56%)
Medulla and/or central axis totally or partly coloured (yellow, rose, orange, red)
Medulla and/or central axis totally white
Medulla loose, the outer part white, the inner part (incl. the axis) lemon to primrose yellow
Medulla and/or central axis dense to compact, differently coloured (rose, orange, red)
Pigments C- and KC-, subcortical, limited to a thin medullary layer under the cortex
Pigments C+ and KC+ yellow to yellow-orange, not limited to the subcortical part of the medulla

Medulla with a wine red pigment. Soralia punctiform, not well delimited, irregular in outline (top view), plane to slightly stipitate but not originating from raised tubercles, fusing together and densely covering the terminal branches. With fatty acids (main)

Medulla with a pink pigment. Soralia well-delimited, more or less regular in outline (top view), originating at the top or raised tubercles, not fusing together. With diffractaic acid (main) plus barbatic and squamatic acids (accessory)
Thallus without soredia and apothecia, smooth to very sparsely papillose, either subdivided into sausage-like elements or distinctly foveolate
Thallus different, with either soredia or apothecia, the surface often densely papillose
Thallus (at least in older parts) divided into sausage-like segments. Central axis often visible between segments, very thin (<20%). Medulla K-, P+ red, with fumarprotocetraric acid

Thallus not subdivided into sausage-like elements, distinctly foveolate. Central axis thicker (23-35%), either K-, P- or K+ yellow/red, P+ yellow orange, with salazinic acid or without lichen substances
Apothecia abundant. Isidia or soralia absent
Apothecia absent or scarce. Isidia and/or soralia common
Branches progressively tapering towards the tips. Thallus shrubby. Ascospores 8.5-11 x 5.5-7 µm. Apothecial disc P+ yellow, KC+ red (alectorialic acid)
Branches irregularly thick for most of their length. Thallus shrubby to usually subpendent. Ascospores 7-9 x 5-6.5 µm. Apothecial disc P–, KC–
Soralia C+ and KC+ red
Soralia C-, KC-
Medulla P+ red-orange and K− or K+ brownish yellow, with protocetraric acid as main substance
Medulla not P+ red-orange and K− or K+ brownish yellow, without protocetraric acid as main substance
Cortex thin, glossy and more or less soft. Lateral branches narrowed at attachment point. Soralia large, >50% diam. of branch
Cortex thick, hard and vitreous. Lateral branches not narrowed at attachment point. Soralia small, < 50% diam. of the branch
Lateral branches fusiform or distinctly constricted at attachment points
Lateral branches not fusiform and not distinctly constricted at attachment points
Soralia without isidiomorphs
Soralia with isidiomorphs
Soralia punctiform and crowded (30-50 soralia per mm2), often becoming confluent and resembling a single soralium (try to observe a single soralium!)
Soralia large (almost as large as the branch at maturity), usually not crowded (15-25 soralia per square mm)
Terminal branches flexuose, twisted, resembling skeletal fingers. Medulla K+ yellow turning red, P+ orange-yellow, with salazinic and bourgeanic acids

Terminal branches not flexuose and twisted. Medulla K-, P- (fatty acids only), or K+ dull yellow turning reddish orange, P+ deep orange (norstictic acid) or K+ slowly yellowish to dull yellow, P+ deep yellow (psoromic acid)
Cortex matt (section!). Basal part of branches with numerous annular cracks. Branching isotomic-dichotomous
Cortex glossy (section!). Basal part of branches usually without annular cracks. Branching anisotomic-dichotomous
Fibrils short and spinulose, densely but irregularly covering restricted parts of branches.  Medulla K+ yellow turning dark red, P+ orange-yellow, with galbinic, norstictic, and salazinic acids
Fibrils short or slender, scattered over the whole thallus, not densely covering branches or restricted parts of branches. Medulla without galbinic acid

Soralia most numerous on terminal branches (last third of thallus length), punctiform and crowded (30–50/mm2), <50% diam. of the branch, often becoming confluent and then resembling a single large soralium, mostly of irregular shape. Fibrils usually numerous on basal parts of main branches. Medulla often with salazinic acid

Soralia numerous both on primary and terminal branches, usually not crowded (15–25/mm2), rarely confluent, >50% diam. of the branch, mostly circular and with a distinct margin. Fibrils usually absent on basal parts of main branches. Medulla without salazinic acid
Thallus distinctly pendent, several times longer than wide, with parallel branches
Thallus shrubby to subpendent, c. as long as wide, with divergent branches

Cortex 4-7% of branch thickness; medulla 24-33%, the ratio axis/medulla ranging between 0.9 and 1.5.  Branches usually strongly irregular, largest above the basal part, foveolate or with transverse furrows
Cortex 8-14%; medulla 12-22%, the ratio axis/medulla ranging between 1.2 and 5. Branches tapering or irregular but then largest close to the basal part, without foveoles or transverse furrows

Medulla K+ yellow turning red, P+ orange-yellow (salazinic acid). Ramifications usually anisotomic-dichotomous. Main branches ± irregular, the segments often slightly swollen in their middle part. Secondary branches mostly of equal thickness over most of their length. Fibrils usually numerous and conspicuous, short to 5 mm long, ± regularly distributed along the entire length of branches

Medulla K+ bright yellow slowly turning orange, P+ orange (thamnolic acid) or K-, P- (squamatic acid). Ramifications usually isotomic-dichotomous. Main branches tapering, the segments cylindrical. Secondary branches distinctly tapering. Fibrils few, not conspicuous, irregularly distributed along the branches

Mature soralia large and strongly excavate at least on terminal branches  (side view!), when well-developed often revealing the central axis. Isidiomorphs always absent (or very rarely present in young soralia only)
Mature soralia not strongly excavate, never revealing the central axis, Isidiomorphs abundant to absent

Ramifications anisotomic-dichotomous. Branches of irregular shape (longitudinal section), often deformed and/or foveolate, sometimes irregularly swollen, the base pale or blackened. Cortex 5–8% of total branch thickness; medulla 50–67%; central axis 28–42%. Medulla K+ yellow turning red, P + orange-yellow (salazinic ± barbatic acids) or K+ slowly yellowish, P+ deep orange (psoromic acid), or K-, P- (caperatic acid)

Ramifications mostly isotomic-dichotomous. Branches cylindrical, never swollen (longitudinal section), the base conspicuously blackened. Cortex thicker (7-13%); medulla thinner (35-55%); central axis ±larger (32–52%). Chemistry various

Soralia excavate only on terminal branches, otherwise plane to slightly stipitate (side view), distinctly circular (top view). Fibrils sparse close to basal part. Basal part often with small longitudinal cracks (at × 50 magnification!). Branches with numerous ramifications only close to the base. Medulla K+ yellow turning red, P+ orange-yellow (norstictic ± salazinic acids), or K+ yellow slowly turning orange, P+ deep orange (stictic acid group), or K+ slowly yellowish, P+ deep yellow (psoromic acid)

Soralia all excavate (side view), of irregular shape (top view). Fibrils numerous on the whole thallus in a fishbone-like pattern. Basal part without small longitudinal cracks. Branches with many ramifications along the whole length. Medulla K+ dull yellow turning reddish orange, P+ deep yellow (norstictic ± diffractaic acids,± zeorin) or K+ yellow slowly turning orange, P+ deep orange (stictic acid group, ± zeorin), or K-, P-
Basal parts of thallus paler than or more or less concolorous with the apical parts
Basal parts of thallus much darker than the apical parts, usually jet black

Cortex thick and hard, vitreous in longitudinal section. Basal parts often with a dirty orange hue. Soralia punctiform, ≤ 50% diam. of the branch. Medulla K+ bright lemon yellow turning slowly orange, P+ orange (thamnolic acid)
Cortex not at the same time thick, hard and vitreous. Basal part never with an orange hue. Soralia and chemistry various

Basal part usually whitish with conspicuous annulations. Main branches tapering (longitudinal section). Soralia large. Foveolae and transverse furrows absent. Medulla with stictic acid group ± lobaric acid

Papillae and tubercles absent. Thallus flaccid when wet. Branches with numerous irregularly crowded, small, isidiomorph-like spinulose fibrils leaving scars when shed, where punctiform soralia (<50% diam. of branch) develop. Medulla K-, P- (fatty acids of the murolic acid group) or K+ yellow turning slowly orange, P+ yellow (norstictic ±fatty acids of the murolic acid group)
Papillae or tubercles often numerous on main branches. Thallus ± stiff. Small, isidiomorph-like spinulose fibrils absent. Norstictic acid and murolic acid group absent
Mature soralia remaining punctiform (< 50% diam. of branch), usually with a few isidiomorphs. Medulla K+ yellow turning red, P+ orange-yellow (salazinic acid)
Mature soralia large (>50% diam. of branch), without isidiomorphs (rarely present on young soralia). Medulla K+ yellow turning red, P+ orange-yellow (salazinic, ±barbatic, ±caperatic acids) or K-, P-
Soralia large, > 50% diam. of the branch (be sure to observe individual, not coalescing soralia!)
Soralia punctiform, < 50% diam. of the branch (sometimes coalescing and forming larger structures)
Isidiomorphs lacking (or rarely present on young soralia only). Soralia distinctly circular (top view), plane or slightly concave (side view). Medulla often with psoromic and/or stictic acids

Isidiomorphs present, few to numerous also on mature soralia. Soralia of various outlines (top view), even with cortex, plane to slightly excavate (side view). Medulla always without psoromic and stictic acids
Basal part with small but distinct longitudinal cracks. Mature soralia usually longitudinally elongated. Medulla often with barbatic acid
Basal parts without longitudinal cracks. Soralia more or less circular or transversely enlarged. Medulla always without barbatic acid

Soralia K+ intensely lemon yellow (thamnolic acid) or K- (squamatic acid). Main axis moderately thick (36-56%) and medulla thin (11-20%), the ratio axis/medulla ranging between (1.2-)2 and 5. Jet black pigmentation restricted to the basal part, with few annular cracks. Isidiomorphs usually numerous

Soralia K+ dull yellow slowly turning reddish orange (salazinic acid). Main axis thick (47-63%) and medulla thin (7.5-13%), the ratio axis/medulla between 3 and 10. Basal black pigmentation often extending on main branches, with numerous annular cracks (6–9.5 mm). Isidiomorphs scarce
Soralia coalescing into nodulose aggregates resembling larger, irregular soralia. Isidiofibrils numerous, covering the soralium aggregates, often fasciculate, fragile
Soralia usually remaining isolated and punctiform. Isidiofibrils absent or rare, not fragile
Main branches strongly irregular, the largest part not close to the base, with foveoles or transverse furrows. Medulla thick (24-33%), ratio axis/medulla between 0.7 and 1.5
Main branches tapering, the largest part close to the base, without foveoles or transverse furrows. Medulla thin (12-22%), the ratio axis/medulla varying between 1.2 and 5
Ramifications mostly anisotomic-dichotomous. Fibrils abundant, in a fish-bone arrangement. With salazinic acid
Ramifications mostly isotomic-dichotomous. Fibrils scattered, not in a fish-bone arrangement. Without salazinic acid
Soralia K+ intensely lemon-yellow (thamnolic acid) or K- (squamatic acid)
Soralia K+ dull yellow slowly turning reddish orange (norstictic acid)
